column2:
Almost all of the property generator scripts use a property named 'database' to specify what database to use. The code uses 'dbname'. Someone probably changed this property a while ago and forgot to update the property generator scripts. It has gone unnoticed because people probably have just used the default value for the database name.

This change fixes the property generator and property files to properly use 'dbname'
column5: Fix property generator scripts to generate 'dbname' property instead of 'database'

column2:
PR #787 renamed the database to 'dashboarddb' from 'dashboard'. This has exposed an issue with the properties generators for docker that use 'database' instead of 'dbname' as the database property name. The property generator files need to be updated to allow docker-compose to set the name of the database. Their default values should also be updated.

MongoConfig uses 
`dbname:dashboarddb`
properties-builders (except for api) use something like this:
`database=${HYGIEIA_API_ENV_SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE:-dashboard}`

Tagging @amitmawkin
column5: Default docker values out-of-sync
column11:
245347807 It does. MongoConfig defaults to 'dashboarddb'. There is no way to change that with docker-compose and the property generator scripts because they only have properties to set 'database'. Hence there is no way to make hygieia use an existing database named 'dashboard'

column11:
245281952 MongoConfig was changed to reference dbhostport but this was missing in the api.properties file.
 satishc1
245310709 I am also getting this.

@amitmawkin could you take a look?
 MarkRx
245328831 The new code takes care of scenarios where a mongodb replica set is used instead of   single mongodb instance format being (host:port, host:port, host:port)
Also the default value of dbreplicaset is false  in the code 
   `@Value("${dbreplicaset:false}")`
the default value is false so it should not matter, and should be backwards compatible if you are not using mongodb replica set and use the old way of dbhost and dbport.
I am running some tests to see if spring needs explicitly to define the optional keys , and not the values..

PR coming from @satishc1 shortly
 amitmawkin
245387902 Fixed now.

Hi,
While trying to run the Jenkins build collector I've found that a place without proper spacing in the logs.

Example:
`2016-09-03 04:22:00,302 INFO  c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - Error getting jobs for: http://10.100.68.2380s`

Note that the '0s' is not separated from the host at the end.
My change should make it so that there is always at least one space between the tokens.

247314111 Number estimates do not show up because your estimate fields are 0:

> "sEstimate" : "0",
> "sEstimateTime" : 0,

This can be because either your feature.jiraStoryPointsFieldName property isn't set correctly or your stories do not have story points on them.

Features in progress do not show up because your epic data is empty:

> "sEpicEndDate" : "",
> "sEpicBeginDate" : "",
> "sEpicName" : "",
> "sEpicNumber" : "",

This can be because either your feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName property isn't set correctly or your stories do not have epics assigned to them.

If these properties have since been updated you will have to trigger an update to get the data in mongo updated. You can either wipe all documents in your feature collection or go into the UI and update something in your stories.

column2:
I have a bamboo collector which I have written. Also for some applications I am using the  Hygieia Jenkins plugin to report the build details. The build details are getting reported correctly in the application dashboard for both the different type of collectors. But in the pipeline view the build details pushed using the Jenkins plugin is missing. All other stats are coming correctly. 

Note : I haven't configured Sonar for these applications yet. ( Don't think it should cause this issue)

I have tried the Jenkins collector and the result is the same. Any idea what can cause this issue and where to start debugging from ?
column5: Commit details not coming into Prod
column11:
243241482 Do you have the Code Repo configured? Also, are you pushing the deployment details into Hygieia via the plugin?
 tabladrum
243406214 Thanks! I got the problem. Data issue .. But I have a bunch of questions regarding the pipeline based on my understandings -
1. If I am pushing the Artifact information using the Jenkins deployment plugin after the build is complete and incidentally that build fails. Then during the next build the change-sets of the previous failed build doesnt get reflected in the artifact information. Just to elaborate if a, b commits where in the first build and the build fails. Next time I build again and this time commit - c also comes. And an artifact is generated . The data that is published in hygieia about the artifact only includes c and not a,b. But the build has information about a and b as a result in the pipeline a and b never moves forward.
2. My build server doesn't have very old builds. But my source code repository has information some 5 months back. So in the pipeline view I am having code as old as 129 Days old which hasn't moved to build. Shouldn't we ignore so old commits data ?
3. Is there any minimum no of commits that we need before we show the stage in pipeline. For a certain pipeline I have mapped Prod and also I can see Artifacts and commits in Prod in the pipelines collection. But the Prod stage is empty. Isn't showing any data. 
 raynaya
244036108 @tabladrum Any thoughts on the above.
 raynaya
245068450 Can you see if your issue is fixed with this? https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/789
 tabladrum
276106175 @raynaya Closed. Reopen if still an issue. satishc1

In UI view.js 'Use Strict' is defined in javascript.  This causes an error on the Jira plugin so it does not render.

Error in console:
SyntaxError: Strict mode does not allow function declarations in a lexically nested statement.     View.js:243

column2:
Bamboo collector, very similar to the Jenkins collector with minor changes
- Captures jobs under a plan and under the sub-plans based on different branches
- Cannot capture build log as it is not provided in the bamboo api

Updated the pr, please check and let me know.  Also check if the screenshots are good enough or not. Thanks!
 raynaya
243236202  This collector works just like Jenkins. The build process is a little different here. They have plans concept (equivalent to jobs) and you can have sub-plans(based on branches). This collector will find the high level plans and give you the list of high level plans available. If you select any high-level plan it will fetch all the jobs under that plan (recursively going inside sub-plans if any present based on branches ) .

column11:
242234901 You can use maven to generate this classes from the core module - modern IDEs will allow you to do this from a "right click" 
 tabladrum
244396483 I found this and am hoping that we can get a more in depth answer. How does mvn know to generate this class? 
 AndrewOrr
244397689 It's Java 6 APT: See this snippet in core's pom.xml:

```
            <plugin>
                <groupId>com.mysema.maven</groupId>
                <artifactId>apt-maven-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>1.1.3</version>
                <executions>
                    <execution>
                        <goals>
                            <goal>process</goal>
                        </goals>
                        <configuration>
                            <outputDirectory>target/generated-sources/java</outputDirectory>
                            <processor>org.springframework.data.mongodb.repository.support.MongoAnnotationProcessor
                            </processor>
                        </configuration>
                    </execution>
                </executions>
            </plugin>
```

244414234 Thanks for getting back to me so quickly. Will mysema look for some type of annotation to know when to build commit or any of the other q classes?

242104026 Is this for local purposes or for hosting the dashboard for others?

If local, you can edit your hosts file to map a hostname (ie. `http://mycname.com`) to an IP address and port (ie. `http://172.14.7.80:3000`).

Hey @tabladrum @amitmawkin, I've noticed that the list of collectors keeps growing. Would you guys like to organize them like the following?

```
/UI
/api
/core
/collectors
  /aws-cloud-collector
  /bitbucket-scm-collector
  /jenkins-build-collector
  /jenkins-cucumber-test-collector
  /jira-feature-collector

  /subversion-scm-collector
  /udeploy-deployment-collector
  /versionone-feature-collector
  /xldeploy-deployment-collector
  ...
...
```

I've done this with another project, and it keeps these kinds of things pretty well organized and tucked away.

Granted, it's a bit of a disruptive change, as it moves a lot of stuff.

- General refactoring of the `LoginController` and `login.html` template.

  - Basically, this line:
    
    ``` js
    $scope.lg.username.$setValidity('invalidUsernamePassword', data);

    This causes `lg.$valid` to always be false, which prevents the `loginData.login()` function from ever being called again.

240721989 feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story
feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName should hold the id of the field that contains the story id. First create a sprint and assign a story to it. Then view that task with a rest call and see if you can figure out which field the assignment uses.

If you are reporting on story points your story will have to have points associated to it. If you are reporting on hours then you will need to set that up as well. In order to get "Features In Progress" to show up you must have an active story assigned to an active epic.

If your configuration was wrong you may need to update the stories / epics / tasks / sprints in jira so that they get picked up again by the collector.

column5: Ram memory usage
column11:
240096236 Haven't experienced this ever. 
 tabladrum
240190462 It looks like you have many instances of the API and the github collector running - am I reading that correctly? Why do you need so many to be running?
 mrpudn
240935107 Ya when you are running all collector at a time then its shows memory issue though you increase the memory size.Its because of API consumption.Make sure that you are closing all connection in collector.
perform GC if you need by looking in to JConsole. In my case I increased my RAM size and have done some connection close operation and GC. now its working fine
 sibaom
240944256 Can you execute the command line "htop" and publish the screenshot of your results to compare with my results?
 benathmane
261279068 @benathmane 
These are numbers we have gathered while running Hygieia on an m4.xlarge AWS instance with 16Gb RAM.

Red Hat Enterprise Linux Server release 7.2 (Maipo)
Linux kernel 3.10.0-327.36.1.el7.x86_64
16GB Ram

We ran the UI module inside apache httpd. The average RAM consumption was 130 Mb for apache httpd. This will go up depending on how many users hit apache. These numbers are for light usage with about 10 people running the UI.

MongoDb 3.2.9 takes up about 1 Gb RAM.

The api process takes up about 1 Gb RAM.

We have 7 collectors running with a total RAM consumption of 7Gb. This usage will go up or down depending on the cron frequency in your properties file.
jenkins-build-collector
versionone-feature-collector
subversion-collector
github-scm-collector
aws-cloud-collector
sonar-codequality-collector
jira-feature-collector
 satishc1

column2:
I'm finding the `docker-compose` script is not plug-and-play on v2.0.0. Is that expected?

Specifically this is what I'm running into:

```
$ docker-compose up
Pulling mongodb (mongo:latest)...
latest: Pulling from library/mongo
5c68a10e9f3f: Pull complete
0110f95fa9c8: Pull complete
0cba4a42bc41: Pull complete
a6eafd7fba3f: Pull complete
703d9d7e0e21: Pull complete
7a4b36461321: Pull complete
5b3580f1488d: Pull complete
913554e7fcc9: Pull complete
2f9b4a452eb8: Pull complete
Digest: sha256:e599c71179c2bbe0eab56a7809d4a8d42ddcb625b32a7a665dc35bf5d3b0f7c4
Status: Downloaded newer image for mongo:latest
Creating mongodb
Pulling hygieia-api (hygieia-api:latest)...
Pulling repository docker.io/library/hygieia-api
ERROR: Error: image library/hygieia-api not found
```

I realized this is just a small issue probably, so I tried...

``` diff
diff --git a/docker-compose.yml b/docker-compose.yml
index 78e2137..b739942 100644
--- a/docker-compose.yml
+++ b/docker-compose.yml
@@ -8,7 +8,7 @@ mongodb:
    - ./mongo:/data/db:rw
   volume_driver: local
 hygieia-api:
-  image: hygieia-api:latest
+  image: capitalone/hygieia-api:latest
   container_name: hygieia-api
   ports:
   - "8080:8080"
@@ -17,7 +17,7 @@ hygieia-api:
   links:
   - mongodb:mongo
 hygieia-ui:
-  image: hygieia-ui:latest
+  image: capitalone/hygieia-ui:latest
   container_name: hygieia-ui
   ports:
   - "8088:80"
@@ -26,7 +26,7 @@ hygieia-ui:
```

and so on. But applying this change to some of the collectors did not work. First, the `versionone` collector. I don't use that so I just commented-out. But then `jira` collector isn't working, and I'd like to use that image. It doesn't seem like `hygieia-jira-feature-collector` is on https://hub.docker.com/.

I can't build them all with `docker-compose build`, and that seems like reasonable behavior ...

```
$ docker-compose build
mongodb uses an image, skipping
hygieia-api uses an image, skipping
hygieia-ui uses an image, skipping
hygieia-jenkins-build-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-subversion-scm-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-udeploy-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-chat-ops-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-github-scm-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-stash-scm-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-jira-feature-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-jenkins-cucumber-test-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-sonar-codequality-collector uses an image, skipping
```

... since indeed the `docker-compose.yml` is set up to refer to images.

I'm just thinking, for plug-and-play demos, it would be nice to grab Hygieia and "just" run `docker-compose` :)

To that end, maybe if they all say `image:`, they should all be on DockerHub ... else, maybe they should say `build:` and refer to the Dockerfiles within this repository. Once consistent, it would be easy to add reference to this in the README or documentation, as a way for someone to get up and running quickly.

Thoughts? Happy to contribute to a solution once I know the consensus.

240430802 Make sure the spacing is correct:

``` yaml
systemLog:
  destination: file
  path: C:\dashboard\data\log\mongod.log
storage:
  dbPath: C:\dashboard\data\db
```

Here's mine, for reference:

``` yaml
systemLog:
  destination: file
  path: /usr/local/var/log/mongodb/mongo.log
  logAppend: true
storage:
  dbPath: /usr/local/var/mongodb
net:
  bindIp: 127.0.0.1
```

Obviously, your paths will be different.

Hi,

Currently, the environments are kind of hardcoded as DEV, QA, INT, PERF and PROD under Configure Delivery Pipeline as shown in the attached screenshot. With our client we have different QA environments , INT environments, DEV environments, etc. So I just wanted to check whether can we have that screen display our environment names specifically instead of DEV, QA, INT, PERF and PROD? Can anyone help me to get to that particular .java file or any other file where these are hardcoded and can be changed as per our client use? I have cloned the repository in my local and can make the changes if I can get some help her so any help is much appreciated.

Thanks,
SUYASH GUPTA.

 tabladrum
239182155 it is a custom db collector, I created a new collector type.
 instigardo
239184701 ok. So, once you have a model, and a collector to store documents of that model type into MongoDB, you need new api(s) to expose the data. See the api module and pick any api as an example. Then in the UI module, you would create a new data factory in here https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/master/UI/src/app/dashboard/core/data-factories

Next you will create the UI widget and consume the JSON response etc etc.

239185900 ok I am able to collect data and store it in mongo, the UI data factory and other elements I have made, I need to know how to use api to create rest service.
 instigardo
239187298 Create a new controller in api/rest. Create a new service in api/service. Optionally create any custom request class in api/request. See examples of existing apis in those.

column2: I have build a collector for octopus deploy in the same lines as urbancode. I was able to get the deploy dashboard up. After configuring pipeline dashboard is  with mappings to the corresponding environments in the project, when the product dasboard is created the Dev, QA , Int and Perf sections are empty. I have deployed the jenkins plugin and it is running as a post build step. I have configured Hygeia in  jenkins to publish build and artifact information. After the run both Deployment and artificat Hygiea gives an ID and 201 created message. Are there any documents to help get the product dashboard setup. The current github readme looks like incomplete in the configuration section.

I copied the Jar file in to a folder on my machine and executed the below command in that folder and it went fine.

``` bash
java -JAR subversion-collector.jar  
```

I have created the application.properties file.where should I keep this file and how do I execute/make use of the file?
column5: subversion collector
column11:
236195940 you can keep the properties file anywhere and use this command line to run the collector:

```
java -jar subversion-collector.jar --spring.config.name=subversion --spring.config.location=<full path to properties file> 
```
 tabladrum
236301373 (from Spring Boot docs) The application will load properties from **application.properties** files in the following locations and add them to the Spring Environment:
1. A **/config** sub-directory of the current directory.
2. The current directory
3. A classpath **/config** package
4. The classpath root

You can be explicit as mentioned by tabladrum, these are just the default behaviors.
 lchase

column2:
Some of the images in the documentation do not appear because
the img src references the root context, which happens when the
documentation website is hosted on GitHub due to the project
prefix ("Hygieia").

This removes the root prefix ("/") for the affected images.

column2: What appetite is there to have non-java collectors? I have a couple of collectors that I have written in python.  They either cover capability gaps of current collectors or are completely new collectors.
column5: What appetite is there to have non java collectors?
column11:
235160927 We probably should create a separate project/module for collectors keeping UI and API as the main project.
 tabladrum
235283910 Once there is a landing spot I'll send some pull requests
 mickfeech
235290502 Perfect. Thanks!
 tabladrum
235295722 @tabladrum This is a relatively small project,  creating multiple repos will make management of compatibility more work, I would recommend keeping 1 repo for the project. If we do want to split it we have to define the rules for version compatibility/release management etc.
 jimzucker
371778271 @mickfeech , Could you please share openshift collector.

 vijayct2001
234551229 I think it's good to have other options.  We are building some Node.js collectors.  It's just less overhead in our minds.  I think that for what these collectors do, it makes sense to have a minimal amount of complexity around them.
 RobertKelly
234615004 All Contributions are welcome....
The architecture around collectors is open and not tied to any programming platform. 
Collectors are an independent piece of software whose sole task is to collect Data .
 We really like where we can do  a push vs a pull, but in case a push is not possible pull is fine.

What Collectors are you working on ?
 amitmawkin
234668243 I have a jenkins collector (build) that works with folders and pipeline, same with a cucumber collector (functional tests). I also have a veracode collector (security code) and an openshift collector (deploy) that I'm working on. 

I'll finish them up next week and send a pull request.  How would you guys prefer non java collectors be stored in the repository if it's no java? Follow same format as the Java collectors?

private CloudVolumeAggregatedResponse aggregate(Collection<CloudVolumeStorage> volumes, CloudConfig config)

column5: Sonar Code Coverage is showing incorrect pie chart.
column11:
233427343 I found the issue by looking at different db entries. If it is  `"name" : "coverage"`we are not displaying it . If its `"name" : "line_coverage"` then it is displayed. Which is fine I guess. 

But the real issue is once a projects sonar details are loaded in the db based on the metrics I had put in the properties file during the first run. Even if I change the property file to add new metrics at a later stage, its not loading the new metrics specified in the subsequent cron jobs.
 raynaya
233428374 If you change the properties file, you need to restart the collector. But your issue points to a good enhancement: Let the UI capture the things that we want to the sonar collector to capture. 
 tabladrum
233432060 Yes. I restarted the collector. Even after that the previously collected stats in the db for a project  is not updated with the new metrics I have specified. 

Yes the UI modification will be really nice to have down the line. 
 raynaya
233433322 Can you delete the existing DB record and re run the collector? The collector wont upsert a record if SONAR's api sends the same date time stamp for the latest scan. Or, you can run another scan instead and look for the new record.
 tabladrum
233435931 Ahh.  Makes sense.  Probably the data has not been updated in sonar since last scan. 

 For new scans the newly added metrics are coming as expected.  
 raynaya
233419909 No its not a know issue.  can you try and debug it, the code for creating the screen is in UI/src/components/widgets/codeanalysis/view.js

233138874 We don't have such tutorial. 
It's very straight forward:
To build everything --
1. git clone http://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia
2. cd Hygieia
3. mvn clean package

To build only API:
1. git clone http://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia
2. cd Hygieia
3. cd core
4. mvn clean install
5. cd ..
6. cd api
7. mvn clean package

column2:
1. Github merges do not move through the pipeline in Product dashboard
   Reason: Product dashboard matches up github commits with jenkins build change set. The change set do not contain merge commits, hence the merge commits never move. 
   Solution: (a) Mark the merge commits as such (b) Do not put merge commits in the pipeline. 
2. Timing issue: When github collectors run slower, but Jenkins plugin pushes build data in Hygieia, in some situation when the build data shows up earlier than the github commits, those commits do not move via the pipeline.
   Solution: Create skeleton commit data using the Jenkins change sets and update them when github commits show up.

#############################################################################

#############################################################################

Add logging to your sprint config to help track down what is going on. Either temporarily throw it into jira-properties-builder.sh or override the command for docker compose and point to a mounted properties file.

```
logging.level.com.capitalone.dashboard.collector=DEBUG
logging.level.com.capitalone.dashboard=DEBUG
```
 MarkRx
232275075 I was able to make it work after some minor changes.

Also I see that  the field `jiraIssueTypeId` can only be set to one value, does this mean that it will collect information for just that type. If yes, what should I do if I want to collect information about all the issue types for the sprint.

Also the "Features in Progress" field is blank as of now. What needs to be done to populate that field.
 rohitstatic
232334821 By changes do you mean config changes or code changes?

Regarding only picking up one issue type - yea I agree that should be changed to allow more than one. Looks like that will require a code change. Wound't be too hard so long as other issue types follow the same json format.

Features in progress will require you to configure your epics field.

Depending on your setup the collector might not be collecting the timing estimate information from your system. PR #682 adds the ability to use story point metrics as well as improved timing metrics by trying two different fields for timing metric information so it can work with different setups.
 MarkRx
232651580 I see that the db has collected JIRA information for a team and the values for `sStatus` and `sState` is both `Done`. The issue falls in an active sprint but my Done coloumn shows zero. None of my sprints shows anything as done. 

My Properties file has doneStatuses mapped to the following.

```
feature.doneStatuses[0]=Closed
feature.doneStatuses[1]=Done
feature.doneStatuses[2]=Deployed
feature.doneStatuses[3]=Fixed
feature.doneStatuses[4]=Duplicate
```

Any help as to why my done field is not getting populated. Also the count of issues differ by a huge amount. Any help in troubleshooting it.
 rohitstatic
232924332 I got it that the WIP , DONE etc are not counts but remaining estimates and makes sense. 
I have all I need hence I am closing this issue.

column2:
Allows each dashboard jira feature widget the ability to specify to report numbers based on story points or hours. Defaults to story points as that should be the most common use case. Configuration only present for the Jira feature collector configuration for now.

![configjiraestimate](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/16699161/72163248-4520-11e6-9d56-e79988b3ba5b.png)

Implementation is a breaking change. sEstimate in Feature.java will be the story points value for all collectors (previously it was story points for versionone and hours for jira). A new field sEstimateTime will hold the time estimate (in minutes for precision) for jira. Jira now pulls hours estimates from the original estimate instead of remaining time due to issues described in #673.

Since I repurposed sEstimate for jira to be story points instead of hours (for consistency - the alternative was to make a bunch of one-off changes for a new sStoryPoints field) previous jira feature data will have to be repopulated for teams that use the jira collector. This can be done by dropping all feature documents. The jira collector will then repopulate everything the next time it runs. This should be relatively fast due to PR #675

column2: When a build is marked as unstable by Jenkins, Hygieia marks this change set (collection of GitHub commits) as a failure (red). The next successful running of this job should mark these as successful (green) and move the change set forward in Hygieia. However, Hygieia does not handle this properly and instead will keep the change set from an unstable build in the commit stage for as long as this data persists. Furthermore, an unstable build should show as a yellow status in Hygieia, providing more clarity to the user as requested in this issue: [https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/84](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/84)
column5: Hygieia unable to handle unstable Jenkins builds

column2:
PR #606 added kanban support to the feature collector widget. For jira it looks like stories are defaulting to be kanban if they do not have a sprint associated to them. As a result stories that are on the backlog for teams that exclusively use scums are showing up as being part of a kanban sprint.

Not sure how to properly address the issue.
column5: Jira features without sprints default to KANBAN
column11:
253004407 Which makes the most sense? @amp5208 @tabladrum 

1.
- Kanban: all features for active sprints and stories without a sprint
- Scrum: all features for active sprints
- Both:
  - Kanban: all features for stories without a sprint
  - Scrum: all features for stories in active sprints

This results in inconsistencies.

2.
- Kanban: all features without a sprint
- Scrum: all features for active sprints
- Both:
  - Kanban: all features for stories without a sprint
  - Scrum: all features for stories in active sprints

This results in consistency but teams that do kanban with a single super long sprint are not handled.

3.
- Kanban: all features without a sprint plus those in sprints that don't have an end date (or end far in the future)
- Scrum: all features for active sprints that have an end date
- Both:
  - Kanban: all features for stories without a sprint plus those in sprints that don't have an end date (or end far in the future) 
  - Scrum: all features for active sprints that have an end date

This allows for us to handle the kanban case that uses a single non-ending sprint. It does make some assumptions to do this. I think this matches the intended behavior for #606 
1. Instead of configuring by kanban vs scrum, have a checkbox to include stories without active sprints.
   When it is checked -> kanban (stories in active sprints + stories without a sprint)
   When it is not checked -> scrum (stories in active sprints only)

This isn't as flexible.
 MarkRx
253799206 WIP @ https://github.com/paychex/Hygieia/tree/feature/TAXSDLC-956
 MarkRx
254325134 @amp5208 are you still working on Hygieia related stuff?
 tabladrum
254492052 PR #903
 MarkRx
262600087 Fixed in PR. MarkRx
231190646 @MarkRx Noticed that too. The assumption may not be correct for everyone. Let me do some digging in.
 tabladrum
231411541 Adding @amp5208 

I don't know if there is a way to programmatically determine the sprint type. In our system we have teams that use kanban by using really long single springs. There are other kanban teams that don't have any sprints period.

Not having a sprint cannot default to being kanban since in the context of a scrum team it means the story is on the backlog.

Perhaps the UI could be configurable.
- Kanban - all features for active sprints and stories without a sprint. Only show Total + WIP?
- Scrum - all features for active sprints. Show total + WIP + Done
- Both - not sure this is a real use case. If it was there is overlap in the data above so not sure how it would work.
 MarkRx
241430070 @MarkRx :  I have reviewed this issue and the open issued tied to it for context.  I used the logic of sprint length to determine if a team was kanban or scrum, based on the assumption you mentioned above.  I am aware that this is not perfect logic; however, Jira does not provide a programatic way or built-in field that I can with 100% certainty confirm if a Jira board is, in fact, kanban or scrum.  Their API does not support this, based on my research.

As for your suggestion, the "both" use case is already covered.  If a Jira project has both Kanban and Scrum stories, the UI will switch between all available Scrum and Kanban boards within the Jira project.  Let me know if you need additional clarification.
 amp5208
252970889 Working on this now.

253001777 @amp5208 do you have teams that have both active scrum and active kanban sprints? Is the 'both' option needed?

I'm looking at changing the sprint type to be a configuration item that is set. As such it doesn't make sense to me for the 'both' case to remove sprint types if no iterations of the type are found. If one type doesn't exist but the user explicitly set it to 'both' then I would expect to see both regardless of if there is data or not.

Also in the collector I have to remove the fake KANBAN sprint data that is being attached to stories if no sprints are found. This is because not having a sprint does not imply KANBAN - it could simply be a backlog item. Instead of trying to deduce scrum/kanban it would be configured in the UI.

column2:
Refactored, fixed, and improved code. Major performance improvements for bulk loads.
Before: load 7300 issues (page size 200) in 45.3 minutes
After: load 7300 issues (page size 200) in 2.45 minutes

Changes:
Performance:
- change delete + insert combos to upserts
- bulk saves instead of save one by one
- caching of epic data
- bulk epic pull at the end of each issues page
- reuse connections instead of creating one per each epic query

Improvements:
- fix improper Exception usage
- fix improper Spring usage
- simplified code
- improved logging
- added basic unit tests

Bug Fixes:
- fix issue where incorrect sprint is pulled when stories have multiple sprints
- fix NPE when story has a comma in the title
- fix issue where stories are lost if query collection is killed before it finishes (sort ASC order for pulling issues since our min date is based on the latest date found in the db)

Planned Changes (for a future PR):
- Add UI option to specify reporting on story points or hours
- Add configuration to specify hours feild
- Automatically obtain Todo/Doing/Done configurations

column2:
Hello,

The current jira implementation seems to pull time tracking data from the "timetracking" field in the REST json response for Stories. This seems strange as time tracking shouldn't be done on stories directly but instead on sub-tasks since stories are abstractions that use abstract measurements (story points). In our system stories do not have time tracking so that field is always empty. As a result the jira widget is always reporting 0 for todo/in progress/done. It does have some fields that appear to be aggregates of sub-task timings (like "aggregatetimespent" in seconds) but those only show up if sub tasks are actually created.

So questions:
1. Why does the current implementation pull time tracking information from stories?
2. Does someone have an example of a system that is currently using the jira collector?

If the current reporting behavior is intentional then I was thinking I would make a code change to allow users to configure the widget to report on either hours or story points. I'm not quite sure what fields to pull for hourly estimates though due to what I mentioned above.
column5: Confusion on Jira Time Tracking
column11:
230614480 @MarkRx  @tabladrum JIRA will normally sum all the children onto the parent so pulling from there should be OK.  I think the salient point is you may want 'story points' vs hours, I would think most people want the 'Story Points' but some of us use hours. So maybe in the pull request to give a choice would be good..
 jimzucker
230896533 @tabladrum @jimzucker @amp5208 Is there a team/company using the jira collector? It looks like the estimates for stories are based on issue.getTimeTracking().getRemainingEstimateMinutes(). If that corresponds to the remaining number of minutes a task has then that seems wrong. The UI would incorrectly report the in-progress hours value and the "done" value as those would constantly be changing when work is completed. For example, if I have (10, 12, 5) (todo, inprogress, done) and a task in progress goes from 5 hours remaining to 3 hours remaining I now have (10, 10, 5) instead of (10, 10, 7). The total number of hours would also be off being 25 instead of 27.

From doc:
Remaining Estimate  Amount of time you believe is required to solve the issue in its current state.
https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirasoftwarecloud/logging-work-on-issues-764478447.html
 MarkRx
231124263 Here is what I might do:

For jira change sEstimate to use getOriginalEstimateMinutes(). Add a sStoryPoints field for story points and pull the value from a configurable field returned in the rest call. VersionOne will populate the sEstimate and sStoryPoints field with the same value. The UI will have a configuration for jira to specify a reporting metric of either hours or story points.

column2:
Hello,

I want to setup Hygieia UI to contact bitbucket, but our repos are private, I can see userID and Password in the java files,

However I don't know how to pass it using ENV variables in Docker or properties file
column5: Bitbucket Private Repo
column11:
230783459 I don't see a way to do it in the UI. Here is how you can do it manually:
1. Create/generate a 24 character key (in this example 'abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwx')
2. Obtain the base64 string of that key
   > echo -n abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwx | base64
   > YWJjZGVmZ2hpamtsbW5vcHFyc3R1dnd4
3. Put that value in your properties file (git.key=YWJjZGVmZ2hpamtsbW5vcHFyc3R1dnd4). There is no environment variable for it so you will have to override the docker-compose command and point to a custom volume with your settings file
4. Obtain the hex string of that key
   > echo -n abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwx | hexdump -e '16/1 "%02x"'
   > 6162636465666768696a6b6c6d6e6f707172737475767778
5. Generate an encrypted password string using tripple DES. The  options your jvm uses may vary. Mine defaulted to using DESede/ECB/PKCS5Padding.
   > echo -n password | openssl enc -des-ede3 -K 62636465666768696a6b6c6d6e6f707172737475767778 -base64
   > 61orEO2iB8UVQI1v4VgFow==
6. Find your database GitRepo record
   > db.getCollection('collector_items').find({'_class': 'com.capitalone.dashboard.model.GitRepo'})
7. Add the following to the options json:

```
userID: "myusername"
password: "61orEO2iB8UVQI1v4VgFow=="
```

Similar issue @ #654
 MarkRx
251996247 Functionality merged in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/835
Refer to the "Encryption for private repos" section in the UI module readme.
 satishc1

column2:
## High Level Changes
1. Making the hygieia jenkins plugin work with Sonar 5.2+ versions. 
2. Capture new sonar metrics available from Sonar 5.0 onwards: new_violations, new_major_violations, new_critical_violations,new_blocker_violations, new_coverage, new_line_coverage, new_lines_to_cover

These new metrics capture metrics of only incremental code thus helping to fix "the leaky water pipe problem"
## Background

From Sonar 5.2+ onwards, SonarQube has hived off analysis of reports as an asynchronous process. This means that when Sonar analyss report is uploaded to Sonar during the sonar:sonar goal, the analysis does not get immediately completed, but Sonar sets an API endpoint called Compute Engine (CE) that gets updated when the corresponding analysis is available.

Hence, with Sonar 5.2+, the Jenkins job will need to monitor the CE API to determine if the processing is complete. After that is complete, can the Hygieia Publisher fetch the metrics from SonarQube for the project.

Also, the CE API can be queried only upto a maximum of 'X' attempts. This value is by default configured to 30 in SonarQube. For max attempts=30, Sonar recommends to make calls to CE API after every 10 seconds.
## Changes made
1. Added additional configuration by modifying HygieiaPublisher and by adding 2 html help files
   i. Max attempts to CE API
   ii. Interval period between successive attempts to CE API
   1. Modified SonarBuilder.java to:
      i) Determine CE API URL by inspecting the log from sonar analysis output
      
      ii) If CE API URL is found, it means the Sonar version is 5.2+. For this, keep polling CE API upto 'X' times with interval of 'Y' seconds. 
      
      iii) If CE API provides a SUCCESS response within maximum number of attempts, continue processing the Sonar resources API
      
      iv) If CE API does not provide a SUCCESS response within maximum number of attempts or provides a failure response, then do not invoke the Sonar Resources API as the report wasn't available. 
      
      v) If CE API URL is not found in the Sonar logs, it means the version is <5.2 and so the processing can continue as before.
column5: Changes to Hygieia Jenkins Plugin- Support for Sonar 5.2+ and for new code metrics
column11:
229362971 Can we put the polling number in the job config? And add some good help file explaining what's it for.
 tabladrum
229426064 @tabladrum - The polling number (called max number of attempts is already added as a job config parameter for Hygieia along with the polling interval. The config items are ceQueryMaxAttempts and ceQueryIntervalInSeconds.

The html files were also added but I have added more information to the help file for easy understanding.
 rohans84
229426329 @rohans84 Did you review docker/sonar-codequality-properties-builder.sh to ensure all properties generated for the container are in line with your changes?
Note: You will also want to update docker-compose.yml to document any new configs.
 jimzucker
229445654 @tabladrum - this changes is only for hygieia jenkins plugin. The Sonar collector already works in polling mode directly to the Sonar Resources API so change is not required in the sonar collector for sonar 5.3 compatibility - it will work out of the box.

_Edit_
The config and sh files you are mentioning does not have configuration for jenkins hygieia plugin and so this change does not require changes in the 2 files that you have mentioned
_Edit Ends_

However, the sonar collector needs to be changed to fetch new code metrics. But that feature is independent of this change and so I will create another pull request for it once I have completed the development.

228935310 I would add as much data as possible (keeping it generic) and store it in Hygieia. What would be some examples of custom metrics?

229255263 Custom metric could be anything like a textual metric or a numeric measure that is instrumented by a custom sonar plugin. These metrics are captured by developing a custom sonar plugin.

For example, we can have a custom sonar plugin that inspects gulpfile.js to determine different gulp plugins used. This will be captured on every sonar analysis by the plugin and updated to sonar database.

I am not sure if we would need to capture these custom metrics into hygieia database as well, but there could be Hygieia widgets that could display these custom metrics for more customized look n feel.

237516181 Hello Guys, Tried yesterday on fresh machine again. It worked very well. The issue was with configuration. I needed to set following values in configuration file.

```
feature.todoStatuses[0]=
feature.doingStatuses[0]=
feature.doneStatuses[0]=
```

So as it is working this issue can be closed. 
 gau1991
237535841 The Kanban view currently shows items that are not assigned to a sprint. I have it on my backlog to fix that as issues without a sprint does not necessary imply kanban (#678). 

Features in progress will show epics that have stories that are being worked on. In order for it to show up your epics configuration must be setup, you must have active epics, you must have stories assigned to epics, and you must have stories assigned to epics that are in progress.

277303182 Closed. The feature widget now has an option to display metrics based on the number of tickets instead of estimates. This is for setups that do not use estimates.

Add logging to your spring config to help track down what is going on. Either temporarily throw it into jira-properties-builder.sh or override the command for docker compose and point to a mounted properties file.

logging.level.com.capitalone.dashboard=DEBUG

232468284 So the log indicates you are not getting any data back from your REST API call. Have you created stories in jira?

What is the output of the following API call? It's possible Jira Cloud uses different API rest calls like Bitbucket does.

Here is a sample raw API call:
https://hygieiatest.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/search?fields=*all&jql=updatedDate>='2016-04-01 12:00' AND issueType='Story' ORDER BY updated ASC

URL Encoded:
https://hygieiatest.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/search?fields=*all&jql=updatedDate%3E=%272016-04-01%2012:00%27%20AND%20issueType=%27Story%27%20ORDER%20BY%20updated%20ASC

You will have to perform the rest call with basic auth. You can use curl, soapui, or login first in your browser and then hit the url

233410702 That json response looks fine.

If you run this query in jira does it return anything?

> updatedDate>='2016-03-01 12:00' AND issueType='Story' ORDER BY updated ASC

Does your mongo db have data in the feature collection? If so try deleting it and allowing the collector to refill. If it does fill up with data check the value of sEstimate.

Also note that until #682 is accepted you may only see 0's on the UI even if you have data in your database. This is because the current code is attempting to pull estimate hour data on stories which may not be using the right field.

234287474 I see. So what is happening is your stories do not have any time tracking data. The "features" list is empty because you have not set epics on your stories.

PR #682 has been merged in. Pull in those changes and build from master. Then wipe the "features" collection in mongo again. Add a new property to your collector properties file called 'feature.jiraStoryPointsFieldName'. Put story points on your stories then determine the custom_xxxxxx field that it is. Finally you will have to reconfigure your jira widget in the dashboard and explicitly set "Story Points" or "Hours". You may have to change it once, save, and change it again to something else and save (aka toggle the field) since this field is new.

```
#############################################################################
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "story points"
# This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's storypoints ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has story points set on it; your custom field name describes the
# story points value you expect to see:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
#############################################################################
feature.jiraStoryPointsFieldName=customfield_10003
```

To get time metrics to show up add time estimates to your story (if enabled) or create story subtasks and add the estimates to those.

To get the features list (epics) to show up add some epics, set them on stories with points assigned, and configure your epics field in your properties.

Also verify your sprint configuration is correct and you are pulling that data from the right field. Create a new dashboard too just in case that needs to be fresh as well.

> db.getCollection('collector_items').find({'_class': 'com.capitalone.dashboard.model.ScopeOwnerCollectorItem'})

If creating a new dashboard and wiping existing data doesn't work (in case something was incompatible after an upgrade) I suggest looking at the mongo documents representing your data and viewing the REST API call the UI makes. When in a browser you can open a browsers development console and turn on network tracking to see the REST calls that are made to the API layer. That will take you to FeatureController.java with a url of something like url/iteration/{teamid}. Following the code will bring you to getCurrentSprintDetail in FeatureServiceImpl which uses the following mongo query:

`@Query(value = "{'sTeamID' : ?0 , 'isDeleted' : 'False', $and : [{'sSprintID' : {$ne : null}} , {'sSprintBeginDate' : {$lte : ?1}} , {'sSprintEndDate' : {$gte : ?1}}]}, $orderby: { 'sStatus' :-1 }", fields = "{'sSprintID' : 1, 'sSprintName' : 1,'sSprintBeginDate' : 1, 'sSprintEndDate' : 1}")`

I suspect that query isn't returning any data.

228581396 Here's a writeup I did yesterday on getting the github working w/ private repos.

Once the instance is up, you can configure a github repository, but only works out of the box with public repositories.  In order to configure it to use private repositories, some additional steps are necessary.

Prior to building the applicaiton, you need to add an encryption key to the github-properties-builder.sh file.  You can variableize it by adding the following line to the config file:

```
github.key=${GITHUB_KEY}
```

Then you can pass it is wht the -e parameter when you launch the docker container:

```
docker run -d --link=mongo -e "MONGO_PORT=tcp://mongo:27017" -e "GITHUB_KEY=j8HWwu+zbnZSg0bC1WsOJYldemGFI3ol" --name github-collector -i hygieia-github-scm-collector:latest
```

You then need to use the encryption key to generate an encrypted password to put into mongo db:

```
db.collector_items.update(
             {"options.url":"https://github.com/<company>/<repo>"},
              {$set: {"options.userID": "<account>", "options.password":    "<encrypted password>"}}
         )
```

As I was doing my research, I came across a forked project of Hygieia that had a [handy tool](https://github.com/pjaol/Hygieia/tree/tools_no_docker/tools) for generating the key and encyrpting.  This was probably the best resource for setting it up that I had found in general.

After doing all of this, I still wasn't able to see the data.  After digging around, it seems that it only tries to get the history data on the first run, so if it ran for the first time before I was able to add the account and password, I wouldn't see the historical data.  To fix that, I just reset the lastUpdated field to zero and it picked everything up on the next run.

```
db.collector_items.update({
    "options.url": "https://github.com/blackbaud/devops"
    }, {
    $set: {  "lastUpdated": NumberLong(0) }
    })
```

Anyways, that's what I have, hope it helps.
 AustinCloudGuru
228581699 Thanks I will look at this tomorrow but I am using a public GITHUB branch (actually the Hygieia/master)  it worked with my old docker VM but when I moved to the new 1.12 docker for mac installation I started getting the Forbidden error but am not sure how it worked in the first place to debug it..

On Jun 25, 2016, at 7:55 PM, Mark Honomichl <notifications@github.com<mailto:notifications@github.com>> wrote:

Here's a writeup I did yesterday on getting the github working w/ private repos.

Once the instance is up, you can configure a github repository, but only works out of the box with public repositories. In order to configure it to use private repositories, some additional steps are necessary.

Prior to building the applicaiton, you need to add an encryption key to the github-properties-builder.sh file. You can variableize it by adding the following line to the config file:

github.key=${GITHUB_KEY}

Then you can pass it is wht the -e parameter when you launch the docker container:

docker run -d --link=mongo -e "MONGO_PORT=tcp://mongo:27017" -e "GITHUB_KEY=j8HWwu+zbnZSg0bC1WsOJYldemGFI3ol" --name github-collector -i hygieia-github-scm-collector:latest

You then need to use the encryption key to generate an encrypted password to put into mongo db:

db.collector_items.update(
             {"options.url":"https://github.com/<company>/<repo>"},
              {$set: {"options.userID": "<account>", "options.password":    "<encrypted password>"}}
         )

As I was doing my research, I came across a forked project of Hygieia that had a handy toolhttps://github.com/pjaol/Hygieia/tree/tools_no_docker/tools for generating the key and encyrpting. This was probably the best resource for setting it up that I had found in general.

After doing all of this, I still wasn't able to see the data. After digging around, it seems that it only tries to get the history data on the first run, so if it ran for the first time before I was able to add the account and password, I wouldn't see the historical data. To fix that, I just reset the lastUpdated field to zero and it picked everything up on the next run.

db.collector_items.update({
    "options.url": "https://github.com/blackbaud/devops"
    }, {
    $set: {  "lastUpdated": NumberLong(0) }
    })

Anyways, that's what I have, hope it helps.

Here's a writeup I did yesterday on getting the github working w/ private repos.

Once the instance is up, you can configure a github repository, but only works out of the box with public repositories. In order to configure it to use private repositories, some additional steps are necessary.

Prior to building the applicaiton, you need to add an encryption key to the github-properties-builder.sh file. You can variableize it by adding the following line to the config file:

github.key=${GITHUB_KEY}

Then you can pass it is wht the -e parameter when you launch the docker container:

docker run -d --link=mongo -e "MONGO_PORT=tcp://mongo:27017" -e "GITHUB_KEY=j8HWwu+zbnZSg0bC1WsOJYldemGFI3ol" --name github-collector -i hygieia-github-scm-collector:latest

You then need to use the encryption key to generate an encrypted password to put into mongo db:

db.collector_items.update(
             {"options.url":"https://github.com/<company>/<repo>"},
              {$set: {"options.userID": "<account>", "options.password":    "<encrypted password>"}}
         )

As I was doing my research, I came across a forked project of Hygieia that had a handy toolhttps://github.com/pjaol/Hygieia/tree/tools_no_docker/tools for generating the key and encyrpting. This was probably the best resource for setting it up that I had found in general.

After doing all of this, I still wasn't able to see the data. After digging around, it seems that it only tries to get the history data on the first run, so if it ran for the first time before I was able to add the account and password, I wouldn't see the historical data. To fix that, I just reset the lastUpdated field to zero and it picked everything up on the next run.

db.collector_items.update({
    "options.url": "https://github.com/blackbaud/devops"
    }, {
    $set: {  "lastUpdated": NumberLong(0) }
    })

Anyways, that's what I have, hope it helps.

column2:
On initial setup of the sonarqube collector, I received 401 errors every time the collector ran. My docker-compose.override.yml did not contain either `SONAR_USERNAME` or `SONAR_PASSWORD`. When I looked at the logs, those fields were defaulting to `sonarusername` and `sonarpassword`. After declaring `SONAR_USERNAME` and `SONAR_PASSWORD` as empty strings in my override file, they were still being overridden with the default value.

On closer inspection, the `sonar-codequality-collector/docker/sonar-codequality-properties-builder.sh` file sets `SONAR_USERNAME` to "sonarusername" using parameter substitution:

```
#Sonar Authentication Username - default is blank
sonar.username=${SONAR_USERNAME:-sonarusername}
```

There are two issues here. First of all, the default is clearly not blank - if `SONAR_USERNAME` is not provided, it will be set to "sonarusername". Second, this is using the wrong form of parameter substitution. `${FOO:-bar}` sets $FOO to "bar" if $FOO is undefined OR if $FOO is defined but null. This makes it impossible to set the username or password to an empty string.

As a result, there is no way to force an unauthenticated connection when using docker-compose, since the properties-builder file will always overwrite an empty value. The expected behavior should be to use the user-provided username/password without a default value. This way the username and password will only be set if provided by the user explicitly.

column2:
Implements proper collector for Bitbucket Server. Fixes issues #609 and #583.

For reference - there are two "Bitbucket" apis:
- Bitbucket Cloud: https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/commits-or-commit-resource-389775478.html#commitsorcommitResource-GETacommitslistforarepositoryorcomparecommitsacrossbranches
- Bitbucket Server (used to be called Stash): https://developer.atlassian.com/static/rest/stash/3.11.3/stash-rest.html#idp1513136

Atlassian rebranded Bitbucket to Bitbucket Cloud and Stash to Bitbucket Server. More information here: https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucketserver/bitbucket-rebrand-faq-779298912.html

This change allows the configuration to determine which one to use and fixes the bitbucket server (stash) implementation.

Summary of changes:
- Rename to bitbucket collector to align with Atlassian naming scheme
- Added documentation about the difference between Bitbucket Cloud and BitBucket Server (formerly known as Stash)
- Fix/implement Bitbucket Server implementation
- Add ability to specify which product to use via git.product in the config
- Added basic unit tests for BitBucket Server

Changes should still work with older versions of Stash so long as the use the REST api mentioned above.

column5: Collector as a service
column11:
226288073 If you want to "push" data into hygieia, all you need is the corresponding API. Share your use case and we can collaborate on the design. 
 tabladrum
226379626 Thanks @tabladrum 

My requirement is to have a service to store the data. Because it is on demand, means whenever I have some data I need to store in MongoDb and I would like to have a service in API project to display in UI.

I have a process which will invoke the collector/data collector service to persist the data. Later user can configure the UI widget to display the data.

Please let me know if you are looking for more details.

Thanks,
Bimal
 bimalvasan
226498598 One more question regarding the relationship. When I create a new collector, which are the  documents/tables I need to care about?.
I am getting an issue in error in below mentioned service call in dashboard-data.js

`var route = widgetId ?
$http.put(dashboardRoute + '/' + dashboardId + '/widget/' + widgetId, widget) :
$http.post(dashboardRoute + '/' + dashboardId + '/widget', widget);
`
Thanks,
Bimal
 bimalvasan
226790460 @bimalvv A collector is a micro service to "pull" the data from data source (e.g. Stash,SubVersion) and push to mongodb. so depending on the source, you may or may not be able to reuse existing model classes and may need to add new ones to core, api and collector projects. Hope it helps.
 sthatip
227331885 Collectors are the microservices such as github collector or jenkins collector etc.
CollectorItems are documents like Jenkins jobs, Github Repo etc. These point to the Collector.
The documents such as Builds, Commit etc has references to corresponding CollectorItems.

Dashboard document has Widget that has ComponenId.
Component document has a set of collector items.

column2:
jira-properties-builder.sh says this:

```
# In Jira, general IssueType IDs are associated to various "issue"
# attributes. However, there is one attribute which this collector's
# queries rely on that change between different instantiations of Jira.
# Please provide a numerical ID reference to your instance's IssueType for
# the lowest level of Issues (e.g., "user story") specific to your Jira
# instance.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's IssueType ID
# listings via the following URI:  https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issuetype/
feature.jiraIssueTypeId=${JIRA_ISSUE_TYPE_ID:-7}
```

It defaults to 7 which made me place in our jira instance's value (6). However it did not work as it was placing empty Feature objects in the database. After looking further the code appears to be looking for a string that is returned from the API such as "Story"

```
if (TOOLS.sanitizeResponse(issueType.getName())
                            .equalsIgnoreCase(super.featureSettings.getJiraIssueTypeId()))
```

It looks like the readme file is correct in that it has feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story. The default value for the properties file is incorrect and misleading.
column5: Jira properties builder instructions wrong for jiraIssueTypeId
column11:
226288183 @amp5208 - please take a look.
 tabladrum
226504382 @MarkRx , Thank you for reaching out regarding your JiraFeatureCollector question.  Firstly, that bash script for Docker was not created by me - I now see that it needs to be updated.  I will send a pull request shortly to ensure that the property file is correct.

In the meantime, you are correct - that configuration is not right.  If in your instance an issue of type story is a different ID, you should actually put the **name** of the ID into that config property.  e.g, if issue type story's ID is 6, put in its name, "Story" into that property.  You can see details of this in our updated README:  https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/jira-feature-collector/README.md

Please let me know if you have any further issues.
 amp5208

column2:
Change provides the ability to specify the spring config location when using a docker mount. Doing so allows for the setting of properties not defined as environment variables without having to build a new docker image. Using this mechanism is more secure as well since it prevents sensitive information leaking through docker inspect or a ps attack.

Example:

> docker run -t -p 8080:8080 -v /logs:/hygieia/logs -v "/vagrant/config:/hygieia/config" --name hygieia-api -e "SPRING_CONFIG_LOCATION=/hygieia/config/allconfig.properties" -i hygieia-api:latest

Note that missing the MONGO_PORT environment variable no longer terminates the container and the echo of MONGODB_HOST and MONGODB_PORT was removed. Since it wasn't consistent, has a default value, and is echo'd anyway it should be fine.

The SPRING_CONFIG_LOCATION defaults to the file that is generated by the property builder of the image if not specified.
column5: Allow use of custom spring properties configurations
column11:
223692742 Update: learned about docker-compose in a comment from @jimzucker. Seems that it can override commands and environment variables. From what I've read a 'docker inspect' environment variable leak isn't considered serious because you need root to be able to run it and hence can already do what you want. Environment variables are not the most secure since they are exposed during linking so should only be used in a confined environment.

https://github.com/docker/docker/issues/13490
https://github.com/docker/docker/issues/5169

Not sure if this PR is useful or not. Maybe for people who don't run docker-compose? I'll wait and see if someone who is more familiar with docker has any opinions.
 MarkRx
225881224 Closing as this is unnecessary - commands can be overridden with docker compose to do whatever is needed. Example:

```
hygieia-jira-feature-collector:
  image: hygieia-jira-feature-collector:latest
  container_name: hygieia-jira
  volumes:
  - ./logs:/hygieia/logs
  - /vagrant/config:/hygieia/config
  links:
  - hygieia-api
  command: ["/bin/sh", "-c", "egrep -vi 'password|Credentials' '/hygieia/config/jira-docker.properties' && java -jar /hygieia/jira-feature-collector*.jar --spring.config.location=/hygieia/config/jira-docker.properties"]
  environment:
  - MONGO_PORT=tcp://192.168.33.11:27017
```

223586056 @MarkRx :  Did you receive this NullPointerException with the newest version on upstream master?  I ask because issues related to the proxy configuration were fixed in a previous issue/PR (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/322)

@mmullerbr :  There is, in fact, a different way to pass in the property file for Hygieia.  You may use the Docker `-v [dockerhost dir]:[dockercontainer dir]` to volume map to a local property file configuration from within the Docker container; more details can be found on the Docker official content page:  [Volume Mapping](https://docs.docker.com/engine/userguide/containers/dockervolumes/).  Additionally, you may have to force a different `CMD` run option for the Docker container, so that it knows where to find your _application.properties_ file; this can be done by adding a new java command at run time at the end of the `docker run` command:  `java -jar jira-feature-collector.jar --spring.config.location=hygieia-jira-feature-collector-new.properties`.  Please see below for a sample command / setup:

Hello,

I am trying to get the stash scm collector up and running and am confused. For starters, Atlassian rebranded "stash" as "BitBucket Server." Going through the debugger it appears that hitting our "bitbucket" server results in the DefaultBitbucketClient being used in code. However I am getting back responses that use "id" instead of "hash", "name" instead of "raw" and "authorTimestamp" instead of "date". This corresponds to the stash api documented here: https://developer.atlassian.com/static/rest/stash/3.11.3/stash-rest.html#idp1513136 and is shown below.

Now it appears that the code for DefaultStashClient has the implementation that will understand this response. However, that class is not annotated with @Component and so isn't wired in.

So I have a few questions:
- How can I use the DefaultStashClient?
- Why does the "Bitbucket" client look for different json tags? Did the api change? Does it correspond to "Bitbucket" (not stash) before they were merged?
- What should I do to get this working?

```
{
    "size": 1,
    "limit": 25,
    "isLastPage": true,
    "values": [
        {
            "id": "def0123abcdef4567abcdef8987abcdef6543abc",
            "displayId": "def0123abcd",
            "author": {
                "name": "charlie",

            },

            "parents": [

                }
            ]
        }
    ],

    "totalCount": 1
}
```
column5: Confusion on Stash/Bitbucket implementations
column11:
223123338 Ok I think I figured out what is going on.

There are two "bitbucket" apis:
- Bitbucket Cloud: https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/commits-or-commit-resource-389775478.html#commitsorcommitResource-GETacommitslistforarepositoryorcomparecommitsacrossbranches
- Bitbucket Server (used to be called Stash): https://developer.atlassian.com/static/rest/stash/3.11.3/stash-rest.html#idp1513136

I think DefaultBitbucketClient.java was supposed to use the bitbucket cloud api but is erroneously mixing the two apis above together. The rest URL endpoint it is hitting uses the Bitbucket Server format but the return data that it is processing is using the Bitbucket Cloud format. I think this was missed because it is possible to get the incorrect code to work against the bitbucket cloud server by setting the api in the config to "api/2.0/repositories/". The bitbucket cloud service will ignore the sha and since parameters and return all commits. If no branching is done then this defaults to returning 'master' (which is what the sha would have pointed to) and all commits (which may be the same as all commits since XXX date in the config).

If both API's are needed then it might make sense to separate them out into separate projects: bitbucket-cloud-scm-collector and bitbucket-server-scm-collector. Documentation can be added to explain what is going on. Either that or a layer would have to be added to determine which API to use. It doesn't matter to me which approach is used.

If that makes sense I can look at making the needed changes soon.

                    String sha = str(jsonObject, "hash");

String sha = str(jsonObject, "hash");
if (sha == null) {
  sha = str(jsonObject, "id");
}

column2:
Currently, the Feature Widget does not support Kanban teams, nor does it support teams which have both Kanban and Scrum teams simultaneously.  With this change, Hygieia now includes both of these use cases, for both Jira and VersionOne.  Related issue can be found here:  https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/505.

Hygieia will now flip through both Kanban and Scrum boards if both exist for a user, also allowing for a user to pause the view switching behavior.  Also, the Kanban view will not include a Done display.  Below I have included reference screen shots:

_Scrum iterations for a single project in Jira, where there are multiple iterations in the project:_
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/8902343/15687889/3a191584-2745-11e6-9995-c9010b990bc5.png)

_Kanban view for the same project in Jira, which also has Scrum iterations within the project:_
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/8902343/15687892/3e67f6a0-2745-11e6-884a-36c55bde4d94.png)

_Note:_ Enabling the new Kanban feature for existing Hygieia implementations may require dumping existing feature collections in MongoDB, to be re-populated with the updated Jira/VersionOne Feature Collectors.

@rashisaxena :  Please validate my fork and ensure that these changes also work for your use case.  Please check this box when completed validation:
- [ ] Customer validation complete

@tabladrum / @jdamick :  Please provide a code review and add inline comments.  I have already fetched from upstream master, but not before squashing my commits; all commits can be reviewed together using the following link:  https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/606/files.  Please only fully accept the pull request once all check boxes on this issue are complete:
- [ ] Internal QA sign-off

223581760 Ok. So I think I know what is missing. Before that, let me explain the links that happens in Hygieia.
Code commits are from Github or Svn etc. 
Builds are from Jenkins and that produces a ChangeSet and Hygieia captures - this change sets matched with commits determine which commits are in Build stage.
The Jenkins build produces artifacts with version number that are deployed to environments such as Dev, QA etc. Hygieia needs to know the artifacts with version number produced in Jenkins build job. That's why the Hygieia Jenkins plugin is there to push that information to Hygieia. 

I think it is also possible to do the same using Jenkins collector, except, the collector needs to know what artifacts information to pull as Jenkins workspace will have everything.

Did you install the Hygieia Jenkins plugin in your jenkins? See the readme under Jenkins plugin page.

223632571 Assuming you have a jar file say myapp-2.0.1.jar that gets built in your jenkins job and the jar file is created in jenkins workspace/target folder, these are the possible values:
Artifact Directory: /target
File name pattern: *.jar
Artifact group: com.mycompany.app
Artifact version: <optional> - the plugin can exract the version from the jar file name. If the jar file name does not have the version, enter the version number here.
